{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509012"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:11:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:11:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11371"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11371"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.36,0.41,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4016"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108820"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4016"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11371"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91183"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5459"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6786"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14773"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40343"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108820"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 12 hour history of abdominal pain and fever. His medical history includes Crohn\u0027s disease, diagnosed at the age of 24 and for which he takes sulfasalazine. He rarely has any flare ups. He had an appendicectomy at 16, but otherwise is in good health. On examination his blood pressure is 118/83 mmHg, pulse 89/min and regular, temperature 38.8 C, respiratory rate 12/min and SpO2 99% on room air. His abdomen is soft, apart from some tenderness in the left iliac fossa. Routine laboratory investigations (haematology, serum biochemistry) do not show any abnormalities. A CT confirms the clinical diagnosis of acute diverticulitis. There is some pericolic fat stranding and thickening of the bowel wall in the area of the sigmoid colon, where diverticulae are visible. No other abnormalities are detected.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discharge home with analgesics and general practitioner follow-up","Oral antibiotics and review in clinic in four days time","Admit for gut rest and antibiotics","Laparoscopy and peritoneal washout","Sigmoid colectomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with acute diverticulitis. In this case the diagnosis is of uncomplicated diverticulitis as there is no evidence on abdominal CT scan of bowel perforation, obstruction, abscess formation or fistula. One or more of the following criteria should be met for the patient to be treated as an inpatient:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEvidence of one of the following signs of sepsis:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETemp \u0026gt;38 or \u0026lt;36 C\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeart rate \u0026gt;90bpm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EResp rate \u0026gt;20\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC \u0026gt;12,000/ml or \u0026lt;4000/ml\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECRP \u0026gt;15mg/dL\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESevere abdominal pain or peritonitis and/or failure to control abdominal pain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMicro perforation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAge \u0026gt;70y\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESignificant comorbidities e.g. diabetes, recent cardiogenic event, recent decompensated liver failure or end stage renal disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImmunosuppression\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntolerance of oral intake secondary to bowel obstruction or ileus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-compliance with care / lack of support system\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFailed outpatient treatment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs this patient has a fever \u0026gt;38, it is reasonable to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadmit for gut rest and antibiotics. \u003C/strong\u003EAnother reason to consider admission for this patient is potential immunosuppression with his use of sulfasalazine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients are often nil by mouth or offered a clear liquid diet to allow the gut to rest so intravenous antibiotics are necessary initially. The antibiotics of choice are usually to cover anaerobic organisms such as metronidazole and a broad spectrum agent to cover gram negative bacteria - Enterobacteriaceae in particular such as a third generation cephalosporin like ceftriaxone. Should the patient have been afebrile \u0026lt;38C, then \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral antibiotics and review in clinic in four days time \u003C/strong\u003Ewould have been an adequate management plan, provided he had adequate home supports. \u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge home with analgesics and general practitioner follow-up \u003C/strong\u003Ewould also usually suffice for a patient who is afebrile and without comorbidities. As this patient is febrile and has a history of Crohn\u0027s disease, he should be given antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurgical interventions such as \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparoscopy and peritoneal washout \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Esigmoid colectomy \u003C/strong\u003Eare management options for complications of acute diverticulitis outlined above. This patient does not have evidence of such complications on the CT scan results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The management for mild episodes of acute diverticulitis will vary, depending on the patient\u0027s co-morbidities."],"references":["You H, Cooper M, Von Papern M, Innes J. The management of diverticulitis: a review of the guidelines. Medical Journal of Australia. 2019;211(9). Available at: www.mja.com.au/system/files/issues/211_09/mja250276.pdf","Sartelli, M., Weber, D.G., Kluger, Y. et al. 2020 update of the WSES guidelines for the management of acute colonic diverticulitis in the emergency setting. World J Emerg Surg. 2020. Available at: https://wjes.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13017-020-00313-4","Gaillard, F., Bell, D. 2008. Hinchey classification of acute diverticulitis. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org. (accessed on 18 Apr 2022)2024. Available at: https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-1451radiopaedia.org/articles/hinchey-classification-of-acute-diverticulitis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91183"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11371"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91183"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T15:57:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T15:58:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4016"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108820"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt"